View the recommandation in https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/identity/ad-ds/plan/security-best-practices/best-practices-for-securing-active-directory and then create a powershell script to test that an on-prem domain follows all.
Seperate into functions, make sure to use extanded logging in case of issues.

I'll help you create a comprehensive PowerShell script to test Active Directory security best practices. First, let me fetch the complete recommendations from the Microsoft documentation to ensure I capture all the security requirements.
Command 'curl -s "https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/identity/ad-ds/plan/security-best-practices/best-practices-for-securing-active-directory" -H "User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36"' completed with exit code 1:
Invoke-WebRequest : Cannot bind parameter 'Headers'. Cannot convert the "User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36" value of type "System.String" to type 
"System.Collections.IDictionary".
At line:1 char:152
+ ... rectory" -H "User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) Ap ...
+                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    + CategoryInfo          : InvalidArgument: (:) [Invoke-WebRequest], ParameterBindingException
    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : CannotConvertArgumentNoMessage,Microsoft.PowerShell.Commands.InvokeWebRequestCommand
 

Let me try with PowerShell's Invoke-WebRequest instead:
Command 'Invoke-WebRequest -Uri "https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/identity/ad-ds/plan/security-best-practices/best-practices-for-securing-active-directory" -UseBasicParsing | Select-Object -ExpandProperty Content' completed with exit code 0:
